This paper discusses data anonymization techniques and their relationship to privacy models. The most relevant sub-category is likely cs.DB (Databases), as the paper focuses on anonymizing data sets. The paper also touches on topics related to privacy and security, which could place it in sub-categories such as cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) and cs.CY (Computers and Society). The use of differential privacy and stochastic t-closeness could also place the paper in sub-categories such as cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.IT (Information Theory).
